title: For Sale:  Concealed Weapons Permit Class (aka Concealed Carry Course) for $59
postcontent:
One of the requirements by the State of Florida to apply for a concealed weapons permit is to have successfully taken a concealed carry course under a certified instructor. Miami Shooters Club provides such a course with its team of NRA certified instructors - who will teach students the important fundamentals of how to safely use a semi-automatic pistol and revolver. Your concealed weapons permit will allow you to concealed carry in more than 30 states.

Miami Shooters Club's instructors carry multiple certifications under the NRA, have traveled abroad to train and receive firearm certifications, and are hand-to-hand self defense experts - having taught multiple seminars for the Miami Dade Police Department. Under their instruction in the concealed carry class, students will learn the mechanisms behind pistols and how they operate while learning how to grip the firearm, aim, pull the trigger, get into a proper stance, and much more. The class also covers many of the legal issues and expected ethics of concealed carry in Florida. The classes are designed for complete beginners who have never touched a gun before... but experienced shooters will learn something as well.

At the end of the classroom portion, students will safely discharge a pistol under the supervision of a certified instructor, as required by the State of Florida. Miami Shooters Club will provide a firearm, ammunition, eye protection, and ear protection at no extra cost.

Classes take place in Miami on Fridays at 6:30pm or on Saturdays at 1pm.

Call now at REDACTED or send an email to REDACTED with your name and phone number for more information.

title: For Sale:  Izhevsk Mosin Nagant M44 with Huber Concepts Trigger
postcontent:
Hello,

I have for sale a Russian Mosin-Nagant M44 purchased from Gander Mountain about 7 years ago.  The rifle is a standard round receiver M44 with side folding bayonet.  The rifle has all of its secondary serial numbers matching.  The primary serial's don't match.

This, post 1938, rifle was made by Izhevsk, and features the following stamping marks: The rifle has the Soviet Crest Barrel Shank stamping; Concentric "00" Accuracy proof Barrel shank; Final black powder proof Barrel shank; Izhevsk Arrow in Triangle (post 1928) Barrel shank.

The rifle's standout feature is the Huber Concepts "Black Teflon Match Grade" Trigger.

While the trigger is by no means truly match grade, it does give you a Mosin Nagant that will shoot economical and hard-hitting 7.62x54r with a trigger that can hold its own with a modern sporting rifle.  Drop in an ATI stock, and you would have one heck of a WV deer rifle.

I will include a Gander Mountain Rifle sock, a Limb Saver recoil pad, and three boxes of Brown Bear 7.62x54r ammunition with sale.  Between the trigger, recoil pad, rifle sock, and ammunition, this is fantastic deal.

I have a JJ Reeb Hofbuchsenmacher in Bonn rifle, the rifle appears to be two 16 bore (gauge) on top SXS and maybe a 11x60 Mauser on bottom.

I understand JJ Reeb was from Bonn and that produced guns from 1870's to 1909(or 1912) (retired) and then passed the business to his sons with the business ending in 1920. Hofbuchenmacher is "court gunsmith" in german. There are no markings on the gun other than the label going between the 2 top barrels and JJR inside the receiver as well as the number 1066 that I assume is a serial number (also on underside of Barrels). I have looked up some other Reeb guns but all serial numbers are all 5 digits long, so I assume this was an early production (roughly 1880-1890).There is "initials" on the bottom of the trigger or some other marking is what I assume is gold. I the top barrels are 16 bore and most likely for 2 9/16" shells. There is tons of engravings all over the rifle/shotgun. The grip behind the trigger guard is made from horn. There is also storage for 4 rifle rounds in the stock (maybe silver?). It is missing the forearm and the front sight, as well as one of the hammer screws does not appear original. It has one set of sights for the shotgun and a peep sight that flips up in the rear for rifle. The take down lever appears to be shaped like an otter or beaver. The front trigger operates the right barrel and when the switch between the 2 hammers is flipped it then selects the rifle firing. The front trigger can also be pushed forward to become a "hair trigger". The rear trigger operates the left shotgun barrel. The hammers are strong and still will move the firing pins freely. From what I understand most of these "drilling" guns are WWII bring backs and many of them were missing the forearms. I have no doubt that it will fire, but I assume that needs to be "old" black powder ammunition.
..
..
It obviously was incredibly high end at one time, however needs restored or would make an amazing mantle piece. I quite simply do not have the funds to put money into it at this time.... I have more pictures but it only lets me list 3 at a time

title: For Sale:  Diamondback DB9, 3 mags, like new
postcontent:
Hello,

I have two Diamondback DB9's in like new condition.  They each come with box, and a total of 3 - 6 round mags.  I AM ONLY SELLING ONE OF THEM, WHICHEVER ONE SELLS, I WILL KEEP THE OTHER.  One is the all black and one has the flat dark earth grip.  I have about 200 rounds through each of them and they have proven to be reliable carry guns.  Fully loaded they weigh just under 16 ounces and truly are the lightest and smallest 9mm you can get.  I have read several mixed reviews about these firearms, but wanted to check them out.  I have had a good experience with them.

On that note, this is NOT a good first firearm.  This firearm is for an experienced shooter looking for an easily concealed pocket 9.  It shoots well and it is accurate, however it is NOT a range gun.  50 rounds go through okay at the range, but after that you hand won't like it.  It can be somewhat picky about ammo and it does NOT like limpwristing.  Most of my 115 gr went through fine and it feeds very well with Hornady Critical Defense.  As with any defensive gun, make sure what you plan to carry will feed reliably.  

If interested, please contact me by phone/text at REDACTED. You should have an Indiana ID and valid handgun permit and we will do a bill of sale. If not, we can do transfer at FFL. OH, please be 21 or older (I know 18 is legal, but my own rule).  Thanks for looking and have a good day.
